tooky
2018-02-20 08:33:09

So another question, from Neil Thomas:

> If you are supposed to avoid talking about user interfaces / buttons etc, can you use Example Mapping to describe the expected behaviour of a set of screens within an application? i.e. when i click on something, this thing happens?

And a related one from Kevin Bradwick:

> If you don’t talk about the solution during the example mapping exercise, when do you?

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 08:43:18

*Thread Reply:* If you want to describe a user interface, use drawings and/or mockups. Examples created during Example Mapping are meant to illustrate business processes and business rules.

Consider this (poor) example: Joe selects "SAV-3" and "CUR-2" and fills in 34 and clicks transfer, then sees a 34 row in the "CUR-2" list", get to the bottom of the business rule you're describing. It might be something like "all transactions should be visible to the account holder". The example could be rephrased as "Transfer £32 from Savings to Current account - see £32 as credit in Current account".

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 08:46:03

*Thread Reply:* The purpose of Example Mapping is to build a shared understanding of the problem domain (banking, trains, whatever). To get a shared understanding of the solution domain other tools and techniques work better (UI mockups, lightweight class/sequence diagrams etc).

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 08:47:18

*Thread Reply:* Example Mapping focuses on what to build and why. UI design and domain modelling focusses on how to implement it. These techniques/tools complement each other.

matt-SmartBear
2018-02-20 14:00:04

*Thread Reply:* I think the only exception I’d say about this is where the problem domain is a user interface.

For example, I worked with a British public service broadcaster on their tv-on-demand web app. It’s pure html / css / JavaScript, using data services built by other teams. The only code they were responsible for was a presentation layer. They still found g/w/t examples were a good fit for discussing and documenting some key / complex UI flow scenarios with the product owner.

So in that context, taking about clicks and swipes made sense.

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 12:51:21

Here is a question from Gilbert Beveridge: > How do you know when you should break your story up? And one from Rajat Sud > Is there a good practice on how many examples should a user story possess, before you have to split the story?

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 12:54:08

*Thread Reply:* At the end of the session, do a thumb vote on whether or not the group thinks this is ready for development. Developers should give it a thumbs down if they feel it's too big. It's easy to get an idea of size simply by counting the number of blue and green cards. Every blue rule card is a candidate to become a new (smaller) story that can be delivered later.

matt-SmartBear
2018-02-20 14:01:26

*Thread Reply:* Small stories are almost always best, so if you can see a seam, slice it!

matt-SmartBear
2018-02-20 14:02:03

*Thread Reply:* I think this is one of the big benefits of example mapping, is it helps you to slice up big stories.

tooky
2018-02-20 22:56:19

*Thread Reply:* “If we could deliver just this business rule, would it be valuable on its own?” If the answer is yes: slice it!

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 12:55:12

Question from Marie McFadden: > Would we narrow down the story to selecting & booking seats (would you say what to exclude from the story? such as how to pay, refunds, cancels?_ A similar one from Sudhir Menon: > Aslak: Question: As a user, can i see this graphic map (seat map) and make my own seat selection? in which case if i want to get on the train, then I can do 2 and 2 and still reserve 4 tickets but on different coaches which meets my criteria?

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 13:06:04

*Thread Reply:* You've asked four questions here. One about selecting & booking, one about payment, one about refunds and one about cancels. Three things might happen for each question:

a) The PO immediately says it will be implemented in separate user stories. It gets written on a yellow card and "parked".

b) The PO confirms it needs to be done, and someone writes them down as rules. At the end of the session someone is likely to say "this is too big, we have to split it", and some of these cards get "promoted" to separate stories.

You may also run out of time because you have too many rules, which is another indication your story is too big and needs splitting.

c) The PO hasn't given it much thought and can't give a definitive answer. It gets captured as a red card. At the end of the session someone is likely to give a thumbs down vote because there are too many questions. The PO or BA now has homework to do to analyse those question and provide answers when you do a 2nd example mapping session on the same story.

As you can see, a) b) and c) all end up with the same result - you get more stories. And your stories remain small.

This is why I love Example Mapping - big, vague stories just don't get through to sprints until they're small and well-defined!

💪 matt-SmartBear
matt-SmartBear
2018-02-20 14:04:05

*Thread Reply:* Yes! Like a filter that stops big chunks of poorly understood story getting through into your dev pipeline and clogging it up!

Question from Daniel Darmon: > What would you consider the difference between examples and acceptance criteria in a story ticket? Are they essentially the same?

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 13:18:56

*Thread Reply:* It depends on how your acceptance criteria are formulated. Most of the time acceptance criteria are formulated as generic rules. Rules and Examples complement each other. Examples illustrate rules. Rules can become code. Examples can become tests.

For example, the Pythagorean Theorem is a rule. The numbers 3,4,5 are an example of that rule.

Rules are generic, examples have concrete values.

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 13:19:38

Question from R.J. Davis: > Any suggestions on how to get this flow working within JIRA? Any good plugins that may make this easier then just throwing all the rules in the card description?

Aslak Hellesøy
2018-02-20 13:22:54

*Thread Reply:* Until there is an Example Mapping plugin for JIRA I recommend using a bullet list in a collaborative rich text editor (such as Google Docs). We might release a JIRA plugin for Example Mapping one day if there is enough demand.

So, I recently (like in the last 10 minutes 🙂 ) had a chance to view the Example Mapping webinar presented by @Aslak Hellesøy. Based on our team’s structure and so forth, I’ve got some questions related to the example mapping process. But, first a little context about my current team

Team Size = 27

of Devs = 13

of QA = 7

of PO/BA = 7

2 week sprint cycle

of stories pulled into sprint on average = 20

Now, for my questions

  1. What is the average team size that should be used to practice Example Mapping? I feel that our team is too big
  2. Given we have about 20 stories to groom, and if we average let’s say 20 minutes per story to go through Example Mapping exercises, that would result in about 6-7 hours of meetings. Is that feasible for a 2 week sprint?
  3. With the team size we have, I feel it would not be feasible to invite everyone to an Example Mapping meeting. How many people should be in an Example Mapping meeting?
theo
2018-02-27 00:56:35

*Thread Reply:* Hi @Robert.S, thanks for your questions. I recommend Matt Wynne's post introducing Example Mapping - https://cucumber.io/blog/2015/12/08/example-mapping-introduction - which should provide you with a bit more advice.

cucumber.io
Introducing Example Mapping·Cucumber
Cucumber. Simple, Human Collaboration
tooky
2018-02-27 01:34:22

*Thread Reply:* Hi @Robert.S - thanks for your questions!

I think the key thing is that you don’t need the whole team there for every example mapping session. You need a representative from each of Dev / Test / Product – sometimes it might also be valuable to include someone from UX, Ops and/or Security.

These don’t need to happen consecutively, you can spread them throughout the sprint. I like to have a list of stories that are candidates for the next sprint and run a quick example mapping session on them before you select the final stories. This turn backlog grooming into work that whole team are responsible for doing throughout the sprint, rather than as a single event. Then when you come to your sprint planning you have stories that are in a good shape, and that the team are happy to start work on.

In terms of the time spent, I think there are 2 things to consider.

  1. Backlog grooming is first-class work. It requires collaboration to ensure that each role is represented. The goal is to have well understood, clearly defined stories, with unknowns (risk) clearly identified.

  2. 6-7 hours, of 3 people producing those well understood stories is definitely an investment, but we hope to realise a return on that investment by reducing the amount of rework due to misunderstandings.

matt-SmartBear
2018-02-27 23:31:57

*Thread Reply:* I would recommend trying it as an experiment on one story for your next sprint, and try to measure whether you think you got good ROI for the time spent,

:webinar: Webinar :webinar: Wednesday, April 08, 2020, 1:00 PM GMT+1 and again at 5:00 PM GMT+1

Speakers - Matt Wynne, Dana Prey & Dermot Canniffe

Remote Mob Programming: Unleash your team's potential with remote, collaborative work

The impact COVID-19 has had in workspaces presents a new set of challenges and opportunities. The good news is, not only has the technology evolved to enable productive remote work, behavioral shifts to better collaboration allow us to effectively do our jobs despite the disruption to our locale.   Mob Programming is a development approach where the whole team works on the same thing, at the same time, in the same space, and at the same computer. 

The team at Cucumber, which is fully distributed, has been practicing remote mob programming since 2015, and we have experiences we want to share.  In this webinar, we will be covering how to:  • Create a blueprint for maximising inclusivity for the neurodivergent team member(s)  • Find success with short, daily retrospectives  • Use tools such as CucumberStudio, Miro, and others to empower collaboration  * *

:webinar: Webinar :webinar: Tuesday, June 02, 2020, 3:30 PM GMT+1 

Speakers - Seb Rose & Dana Prey

FROM TEST MANAGEMENT TO CONTINUOUS DELIVERY The days of annual releases and six-month test cycles are coming to an end. Organisations facing rapidly changing business situations find that the ability to release software more frequently is key – hence the industry interest in Continuous Delivery (CD). For many of us, this is going to be a big change – and we know that big changes are risky.

This webinar will define Test Management and Continuous Delivery and go on to explore typical challenges you’ll encounter on your journey towards CD. We’ll describe small steps that you can use to mitigate the risks of changing the way you work, and the value that can be released from the start.

Breaking out of traditional silos and embracing wider, earlier collaboration is a daunting prospect. By the end of this webinar you’ll be able to explain the benefits that are on offer and describe the first steps of the journey. medium=social&utmsource=slack&utm_campaign=webinar|Register here>

:cucumberbdd::webinar: Two Part Webinar Series: Why hasn't TDD taken over the world yet?

Tuesday, July 28, 2020, 3:00 PM GMT+1 and Thursday, July 30, 2020, 3:00 PM GMT+1

Test-driven development (TDD) is a development technique where you must first write a test that fails before you write new functional code. It relies on the repetition of a very short development cycle: requirements are turned into very specific test cases, then the code is improved so that the tests pass.

Sounds great, right? Then why hasn’t TDD taken over the world yet? The team at Cucumber has invited some friends to discuss.

Join us for a 2-part panel discussion as we work out how to avoid common obstacles, pitfalls, and generally some best practices around employing TDD for your organization. Session 1: When does TDD fail and why? (Tuesday, July 28th) Featuring: • Jon Acker   • Dave Farley   • Clare Sudbery   • Denise Yu   • J.B. Rainsberger   • Matt Wynne   Session 2: How can we get more people able to enjoy TDD? (Thursday, July 30th) Featuring: • Steve Freeman   • Paula Muldoon   • Emily Bache   • Jonan Scheffler   • Lynoure Braakman   • Sabrina Leandro   • Dave Farley   • J.B. Rainsberger   • Matt Wynne   medium=social&utmsource=slack&utm_campaign=school|Register for any session>, and we’ll automatically register you for both to make it easier to participate.
